# Day 2 – Biotechnology & Water Quality

## Activities
- Visited a biotechnology research center to learn about agricultural research.
- Learned how scientists study corn DNA and use selective breeding and DNA crossing to develop stronger, more efficient crop varieties.
- Explored how biotechnology helps improve food production and supports agriculture.
- Participated in a water quality lab where we tested different water samples.
- Learned about turbidity, pH levels, and other indicators of water quality.
- Used water testing strips to measure the health and safety of different water samples.

## What I Learned
Today, I learned how biotechnology is used to improve agriculture by studying corn DNA and developing crop varieties that are more productive, disease-resistant, and efficient for feeding a growing population.
I also learned that water quality can be measured using several factors, including turbidity, which describes how clear or cloudy water is, and pH, which measures how acidic or basic the water is. 
Using water testing strips helped me understand how scientists quickly evaluate the health and safety of water in different environments.

## Favorite Part
My favorite part of the day was visiting the biotechnology research center because it gave me an inside look at how scientists use genetics to improve crops that people rely on every day. 
I also enjoyed testing water samples because it was a hands-on activity that showed me how environmental scientists monitor water quality. 
It was interesting to see how both biotechnology and environmental science use data and experimentation to solve real-world problems.
